cs.PL, cs.LO, cs.TY, cs.SE, cs.FL. 

The paper is about a core calculus for modelling Scala, which is a programming language. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.PL (Programming Languages). The paper also discusses a proof strategy for reasoning in the calculus, which suggests that it could belong to cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science). The paper deals with abstract type members, which are a type-related concept, indicating that it could belong to cs.TY (Type Theory). The paper also discusses the challenges and paradoxes caused by abstract type members, which suggests that it could belong to cs.SE (Software Engineering). Finally, the paper presents a machine-verified version of the proof in Coq, which suggests that it could belong to cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory).
